    <text type="letter">
        <body> 
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc_jm.00398.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>  
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="printed"/>Medical Superintendent's Office.</name>
                    <name type="place" rend="center">INSANE ASYLUM</name>
                    <name type="place" rend="center">LONDON ONTARIO</name>
                    <date when="1891-10-29"><handShift rend="manuscript"/>29 Oct <handShift rend="printed"/>18<handShift rend="manuscript"/>91<ptr target="loc.08290_n2"/></date>
                </dateline>  
            </opener>
            <p> Many thanks, dear Walt, for "The Record" (this moment received) 
                containing "Whitman's Nightfall" (daylight is certainly fading but "night" is not yet). 
                When night <hi rend="underline">does</hi> come it will be moonlight and full of stars&#8212;I 
                am not in any sense terrified of it. All quiet and well here. 
                Meter<ptr target="loc.07230_n2"/> jogging along hopefully&#8212;it has 
			    been under a bit of a cloud for a few months but I think I see some clear sky ahead now. 
			    I am reading Wigston's book on Bacon<ptr target="loc.08179_n2"/> which I mentioned to you a few 
                days ago<ptr target="loc.08290_n1"/>&#8212;he points out in a striking manner how B.'<hi rend="underline">s</hi> 
                Henry VII<ptr target="loc.08176_n3"/> dovetails in between S.'<hi rend="underline">s</hi><ptr target="loc.08290_n3"/> Richard III &amp; S.'<hi rend="underline">s</hi>
                Henry VIII&#8212;the same man <hi rend="underline">must</hi> 
			    have written all three</p>
            <closer>
                <signed rend="right">R M Bucke</signed>
            </closer>
            <pb xml:id="leaf002r" facs="loc_jm.00399.jpg" type="recto"/>
